segments.text: build it.
Number three, you're going to fire at least three or four architects.
They fired three.
It took them two and a half times longer to build it than they thought.
And it cost them twice as much.
It cost them $12 million.
It's a magnificent edifice.
And I'm glad they did it and all that.
But I really see what follows.
But you were out of the loop at that point.
I was out of sync.
See, what bothered me was using annual giving money to pay utilities on a building they didn't need to.
You know, you pay janitorial service, you pay for a big building like that, that land, it's not state property.
At least we hung up.
Oh, I've got to tell you a funny story.
When we expanded the MSC in the early 70s,
general of the Dean of Students, General Hennigan, was chairman of the expansion.
Well, boy, no one knows this, except Tom Cherry and Nestle and Diebel.
Diebel, they know it.
We'd been occupying the West End.
See, the way this started,
We, former students, raised the money for the down payment on the MSA.
I think it's about $250,000.
We bought, that was our annual giving project when it started in 1942 that I read.
That was give to the dream, all we had when we were in school was the YMCA.
So now we're going to have the memorial students there dedicated to the men who gave their lives in World War II.
So they raised about $250,000.
Of course, the building cost several millions.
But that paid for the architectural study.
It paid for the other necessary things.
So the former students got credit for the building.
But the building cost a hell of a lot more than we raised.
So we had an office in it.
Our deal was, give us an office in it.
Wayne Stark's on one side of the West End, and we're on the other side, which we outgrew real fast.
So it was the next expected job.
Hell, I was looking all over the campus for sites and locations to build.
At one time, we were going to take the old Gilchrist home, which John Colas is in now.
We're going to use that as a base and add on to the back of it.
And Jack Williams said, yeah, now ain't that what I need, the former students in my backyard?
So I always said, you're right.
So then I came up with the idea from the architectural plan.
Dee Dee Matthews, the architect.
I said, Dee Dee, why can't we do this?
I said, boy, he jumped on that.
Well, I got Cecil Stewart to do a study.
And with Cecil Stewart helping D.D.
Matthews, they designed it.
But I couldn't get the authority from the board to do it.
And Rudder wouldn't push it either.
Rudder was suspicious of that.
Hell, he wanted office space himself.
If you're going to build that, he wanted it, see?
All Britain saved the day.
All Britain went in there and told it.
Regents what was going to happen and what we ought to do.
And so we'd pay for it all.
Well, Bob Walker and Cop Forsyth, Bob Walker got Cop to give him a million and a half dollars.
That's what he paid for.
And so with that, of course, the furnishings, we put most of the money in the lobby and the offices we kept pretty sparse.
But we only had $120,000 to furnish it with.
That's not a lot.
We had that beautiful carpet and all that stuff.
Oh, yeah, here's the point.
So O'Hanigan didn't say anything to me about anything.
And of course, I told the people, now this is going to be a building of the MSC.
So it'll be set up for booking.
You can book the facility, our boardroom and our lobby for use for faculty retirement, staff faculty retirement.
It'll be part of the MSC for booking, so-and-so.
And being as how we're in the building, we ought to be on the Centrix.
Our number ought to be an 845 number.
Oh, yeah, that's fine.
Well, about two years later, I got marched on.
And old Tom Cherry and Lee Diebel came in there.
He said, how'd you pull it off?
Well, right then's when I should have had the Academy Award.
or the Distinguished Alumni Award for acting.
I said, pull off what?
I knew damn well what.
He said, you don't have an electric meter.
You're not paying electric for this facility.
And you're on the centric system, and so on, and so and so.
You're getting janitorial service.
I said, well, gentlemen, wait a minute.
I said, you know, Dean Hannigan was in charge of this, and we agreed.
They said, yeah, you conned him, didn't you?
I said, no, sir.
I said, this building, this facility is used for the Memorial Student Center.
And John Richards will be booking this facility for use for continuing education or whatever else.
This lobby and these offices are available, except for the private offices, are available
for student use and the use of the university.
This is a university facility.
I said, we've got the three levels here.
We've got the offices up here.
And we've got the mail room in the basement.
I said, this has made a perfect setup for everybody concerned.
I said, it didn't interfere with any function of the university.
And it added to it.
It added another million some dollars to the building, which will be here for whatever.
We'll probably move this office in time to come, but it'll still be available for .
They said, well you've sold everybody else but us.
I said, look, we get billed by the university for our telephone bill.
We get billed and we pay our bills properly.
I said, I bet you have agencies that don't pay as properly as we do.
They said, that's right.
And I said, let's see, what else did I say?
I said that the association was in business to do so and so and so.
I went out and gave them the biggest bullshit story.
made them feel bad they'd ever called on me and complained about this.
But all of a sudden they woke up, Diebel's the one that picks these little auditors.
He picked that up and said, look at these guys.
Here's a private corporation we got in the building and they're not paying rent or nothing.
I said, well, you're lucky to have us here.
Just think what we do.
I said, we're on the committees and we serve everybody.
We help out.
We raised money for students and student activities.
Wayne Stark, we've always been tied in close to Wayne and his programs.
We worked with the students.
This is an absolutely perfect setup.
I said, you couldn't have it any better.
I said, what if we were off in some thing in the corner of the campus?
It wouldn't be nearly as effective.
Of course, I just...
They were ready to pull out a checkbook and give you more.
We've done you wrong.
But I'll tell you, my big surprise and shock at the fact that he was questioning a thing like that.
Well, it is.
Let me ask you, let's kind of close up, because I know I'm taking an awful lot of your time.
I appreciate it.
I may come back to you.

But in the 10 years, 10, 12, 13 years now that have passed since you've been in an official capacity with the former students, and you've had a little more objective view maybe of the university, what do you see as having happened that has been particularly good or particularly bad in these past 10 years?
Of course, the next question I'm going to ask is, where do you see where we're going to go from here?
I think the university has just done a fantastic job.
I think the efforts to try to bring the physical plant here up to meet the needs of 41,000 students has been tremendous.
They still have some time to go.
They've got to finish this construction across the track and get business moved over there, readjust their use of these buildings.
That's right.
That whole campus is a post-1980 campus.
That's right.
Exactly.
So I said, the physical plan, I said, right now they're using laboratories all hours of the day and night.
But I think the future is we're gearing a lot of it for high tech.
And that's where it's got to go.
I think two things.
I think, one, liberal arts has got to take a stronger position because of the universal nature of our university.
We now have to gear our university for worldwide.
They're talking about this economy is a universal economy.
Our education has to be the same way, which means we're going to have to be bigger and stronger in modern language and in history.
Our people have to be a little better educated intellectually, along with the high tech.
High tech and engineering and science and other things has got to meet the needs of just, what, seven years away.
We're entering into a new century.
And business is going to be different in all parts of the world.
Our technology programs of the past are job related, doing jobs, a specific task in electronics and mechanics and whatnot.
I think probably education has got to gear itself more to the intellectual.
We've got to compete with leaders from Japan and from Europe.
Europe people seem to be better educated than our people are.
It depends on the technical or engineering curricula, whether you can.
do all this, but I think we're geared in that direction, and I think that we're getting a different type of leader, too.
We're getting a psychologist as president of the university.
I think one thing I think that's just fantastic is the way we conduct these commitments.
They're killers now for the registrar's office.
They're killers for the president and the deans and people.
But like we have seven of them, imagine they did four of them.
We had one at 11, one at
two, one at 7.30, then they had one at Saturday morning.

But the fact that they give them a diploma that's completed, the former students gives them a little miniature diploma for their billfold, and the fact that the president hands themsee, every other major university in the world bails them the diploma.
No one tries to do this.
I never thought we'd do it.
I said, that's one thing that the new registrar will drop.
Listen, he's gung-ho for it.
Mobley's gung-ho for it.
And Mobley gets in there, those little pre-commencement, and they're just wondering.
Gives everybody a nice book.
I get to give you a book called Neil Ford Architect.
I love that because I know a lot of people in it.
Aggies, Brooks Martin, and lots of other guys.
So I love it.
But anyway, I'm just saying.
So they give you that personal touch.
Yeah.
We're a big 40,000 student.
We're going to get bigger.
And, of course, I think it's too bad.
I just hate turning down a well-qualified student.
It just breaks my heart to see, especially one of our former students, has a grandchild or something like that.
And I think something should be done to offset that a little bit.
I just hate to say you've got 16,000 qualified applicants, but we're only going to take six.
We're only going to take 2,000 transfer students.
And so many graduate students and so on.
Of course, the graduate students, I realize that's got to be limited.
You can only take, your faculty can only handle so many in the advanced degrees.
I realize that.
But the undergraduate degree, I think that's got to continue to be strong.
We can't ever neglect that.
The teaching of freshmen has got, the nicest compliment I heard said was by my scholar.
His name is Daniel Kent from Austin.
He said, my buddies over there are in class with hundreds of people.
And over here, I'm in class with
tens of people.
I've just got 20, 30 people in my class.
He said, this is far better teaching university than the University of Texas at Austin.
From what he hears, his sister goes there and his best friend goes there.
He got a presidential scholar to come here.
And he's thrilled to death with it.
But he just thinks his teachers are wonderful.
He says, my faculty members are just great.
And one of my lady friends in San Antonio's son is here.
I'm going to tell you a story about that.
A year ago, sophomore year, he was having a terrible time with accounting.
This is a guy that puts on magic shows.
This is a guy that entertains.
He's an out people person.
Yeah.
And he's taking accountants.
Because his dad says, oh, learn to be an accountant.
Take business and accountants.
So he's over here.
And every Valentine's Day, his grandmother, who is a lovely lady, but oh, she's rich as hell.
And she sends me some money to buy a Russell Stover box of Valentine's.
See, his mother, who was the same age as my daughter when she died, who's this woman's daughter.
She's a granddaughter, see, this kid.
So the boy said, oh, they're having a terrible time.
The emperor's down and so on.
I said to him, he said, wait.
He said, I don't know.
He said, I think I'll transfer.
I said, wait a minute.
Why don't you go see your advisor and tell him you'd like to get permission to talk to people in liberal arts?
I said, you ought to transfer to liberal arts.
You shouldn't be taking accounting.
I said, you're not going to be an accountant.
I said, you need to get into modern language, get into history, and get into literature, things that you really like.
I said, you're a good reader.
I said, you do well on tests and all that stuff.
This year, this Valentine's Day,
I go pick him up, and he's got an apartment off campus at Northgate.
Those nice apartments are just down Nagle Street.
And I'm thinking, well, boy, he's happy.
I said, we're going to go.
Oh, let's go to so-and-so.
I said, well, you're smiling this year.
He said, boy, that advice you gave me, I switched to liberal arts.
He said, I'm making straight A's.
I joined a fraternity.
I said, get in a fraternity.
You didn't get in the Corps.
I said, get in a fraternity.
Go around and pledge these outfits.
They want you.
You got the money.
So got in the fraternity down there on Texas Avenue or something like that.
He loves his buddies he's made in there, he's made friends, he's made his friends, and he's just gung-ho, see?
A little bit of...
I think I said, I think one nice thing about the university now is there's more opportunities for more divergent types, I guess.
And that's part of being a big university.
And you know what this university has that no one has?
All these... Oh, that's a mower.
All of these student organizations.
Mm-hmm.
I've never seen it like that.
That's right.
Up in the MSC, there are hundreds.
That's a training ground.
Yeah, for leadership.
That MSC council director, that's fabulous.
No one's got anything that big.
And over there in Carolyn A. Dare's office, man, you can get anything there from climbing mountains in Italy to skiing down mountains.
I mean, these clubs, there are hundreds and hundreds of clubs.
I became so aware of that.
Of course, I used to
raise money and finance them, just like I did for the Calvary.
I did that outside of the budget.
And like the soccer team and the cricket team and the rugby team and all those things.
I was on that MSC board.
What was it?
Advisory Council, I guess, for some years.
That was really interesting.
I enjoyed that.
I never did them much good, but it was interesting.
The students here get a well-rounded education.
They really do.
I'm impressed with them.
And I hope my granddaughters will.
Of course, I'll sure take them over there.
They're good students and they're going to be, and one of them says, Papo, would you mind if I took education?
I said, I'd be thrilled.
I'd be thrilled.
I said, anything you want to take, I said, except if you're going to take music, you can't go to A&M.
I said, A&M does not have a music, it never will have one.
We've got a department now, but no degree in it.
People can take courses over there, real good.
Of course, they can learn to sing and play and do all that kind of stuff, but they're not going to ever get a degree in it.
I don't think we need a college of music.
And we shouldn't ever have one.
But it's good to offer courses in it here.
That's all right.
They have some good instructors and people.
I don't know if they have any professors or not.
The university is just a
The only problem I see is they can't accommodate these good students.
They can't get in.
That just breaks my heart.
But actually, we're limited by facilities and by faculty.
We have to have enough good teachers, and I hope we never lose, I hope the faculty never does, let's research and that sort of thing, take over from the teaching role.
Yeah, that's going to be a problem.
It's already a problem.
Already a problem, right?
What about the Corps?
Do you think they're going to continue to exert some kind of spiritual or moral...
I think the Corps is always going to be here, maybe smaller, smaller.
I think we'll have 1,000 to 1,500 people in it.
I don't think it's ever going to be the big influential Corps that it should be because there's two problems.
One, the type of student that comes out of the homes of Texas and America today are not conducive to high states of discipline, especially where they get hollered at.
And as a freshman, they're going to be hollered at.
It's what it is.
It's Marine Corps training.
It's just making beds and shining your shoes.
That's hazing, see?
I think the push-ups and all that sort of stuff, that shouldn't harm anybody.
But see, kids don't like to do that.
It's a thing that's distractive to them.
It's distractive to the faculty.
They have to listen to people bitch about it.
A little girl told an old Henry Wendler columnist, but who's in charge down there?
I said, well, Henry in charge of what?
Who's in charge of hazing?
I said, Henry, the people that are in charge of hazing are the people that are doing it.
He said, Buck, you're pretty damn smart.
He says, you're right.
He said, I wanted to find out if you knew who the hell is in charge of hazing.
He said, I'll tell you what I did.
I talked to Mobley up here, and I said, Mobley, the girl on my scholarship has got out of the Corps.
And he said, they just hazed her too much, and she couldn't accept that, so she got out.
He said, now, who's in charge of that?
What happens to that girl down there?
Mobley says, well, I don't know.
She'll have to talk to John Coldis.
He says, that Coldis comes under student .
So he came down here, went over, talked to Coldis.
And Coldis says, well, that's in the Corps.
You'll have to talk to General Darling about that.
So he goes over and sees General Darling.
And General Darling says, wait a minute.
We have a lady, a major here, that'll take you down to the dormitory.
So he took this woman, Major Tober, to the dormitory.
They found the upperclassman of the class woman, or man, I don't know who was doing it, but it was Hazender, see?
And he said, Henry said, why did you tell this girl that she couldn't keep her civilian clothes in here, that she couldn't go to the bathroom after 10.30 at night?
If she had to, she had to pee in the sink and that sort of thing.
And the sophomore said, because that's tradition, sir.
He said, hell, if it's tradition, the sophomores are going to keep hazing the freshmen, see?
The commandant can't stop that.
You can't have someone sleeping with everybody in the court.
So as long as you've got a hazing system, which, see, it's a quasi-military thing.
That's really not military.
It's like boot camp, see?
It's boot camp.
It's like OCS.
And when you have that situation, whether it's uniforms, whether it's shoes,
whether it's beds to be made and whether it's spoken words said in West Point, Annapolis, Air Force Academy, you can't eliminate it.
It can't be eliminated.
Now, the former students got a big committee challenged by the regents to come up with a study, and the Corps has been studied to death here.

What they need to do is let the Corps study itself gather all these seniors and juniors and so on, like I used to take them all out of the country, and I determined right then, not a damn thing I could do or say
or the former students are going to say.
All I told them about was what your goal has to be is to make the Corps so attractive, like a fraternity or sorority, that the kids want to be in it.
And it could work.
They want to be in it.
Now, if you can create that atmosphere in the Corps, well, you'll have 3,000 kids in the Corps.
That's about how many of those 12 dorms will hold, about 3,000, 1,500 on each side.
And I said, when you get that,
Then you can call them out and just take specific ones of the Corps.
But see, what I'll say is this.
The quality is so high.
God, those kids, they're gung-ho, all-American kids.
Good-looking and proud, you know.
But there's not very many of them.
They've only got about 1,600 over there.
It's going to be tight with the funding and all that kind of stuff.
It's going to be a lot of power.
Those damn dorms aren't worth a damn.
They never have been.
I couldn't believe it.
You know, my class was the first ones in those dorms.
Freshman year, I lived in Milder Hall.
Then at summer of 38, opened in 39.
Well, they started in 38.
And when I saw those dorms, they're just like prison barracks.
And hell, they're conducive to hazing.
It's just terrible.
They got them air-conditioned, and they got carpets on the floor so they're not as noisy.

but but uh hell those you know i said god you could slaughter 100 people up here no no just put a guard at each end to watch the buzz don't come in you know that that was my first impression he and him was not here but when i was in school at texas in the 50s 52 to 56 i remember one year i drove back made a loop down through the campus on this this was gravel road i believe millican was right and i remember seeing the dorms and that
Like a prison.
Look, it's just gruesome.
I couldn't believe it, yeah.
I didn't know much about A&M, although Louisiana people, you know, A&M was well regarded.
When you look at Hart Hall and Walton Hall and Puryear and Law and Puryear and Hart and Walton, they're built on a ramp system.
You come in and you've got three or four rooms.
No, you've got three rooms and a shower and a bath.
Then you go up, you've got three.
So you have up this ramp.
Well, you can only kill about three rooms of kids at a time that way, see.
What I'm saying is it's not as conducive to hazing as the long cell block system is.
I hated those doors because they're not conducive to study.
They're not conducive to anything except put a bunch of prisoners in.
Lock the damn door and throw the key away.
That's a good analogy.
That's interesting.
Well, Buck, I appreciate everything and all of that.
keep in touch, and in fact, as this thing develops, I'll come back.
Oh, well, I'm sorry we took so long.
Oh, no, I'm not sorry.
It would take long.
I don't want to burn you out completely.
I may come back.
But if you will, as this thing develops, I'll call on you to kind of look at it.
You've done this before.
Tell me where I've erred.
Any, well...
